content: I'll never get a Christmas card from the Fed. üòÇ

Here's an audit exercise:
How much was Powell personally down in Q4 '18 when his autopilot balance sheet roll off & rate hikes blew up & markets dropped 20%?
How much was he up in '19 when he flip flopped & cut rates 3 times with UE at 3.5%?
Audit this & then see the conflict.

Not suggesting anything untoward, but just the blatant appearance of conflicts of interest undermine the independence of the Fed, puts into question their motivations & their policies as they have personal financial incentives tied to appeasement.
None of this is transparent.

Wasn't Janet Yellen's 1st act as Treasury Secretary to come out in favor of buybacks for banks, the very banks that paid her $7M in speeches?

I'm not saying ex Fed Chairs don't have a right to make money but to see economists that never were very wealthy suddenly cash in smells

Why would any Fed Chair do ever anything to upset Wall Street when they now have well established expectations of making millions of dollars in speaking fees paid for by the very banks they were supposed to supervise?

How is that not Banana Republic like type stuff?

Why is that topic off limits?
It's such an obvious question to ask, but no reporter will touch it with a 10 foot pole for I suspect they'd find themselves fired within 5 minutes of asking the question.

I'm not accusing him of anything, but there is zero doubt that he has massively financially benefited from the policies he's implemented & insists on maintaining.

And frankly, if the Fed is so transparent, he should disclose how much his holdings have increased since 03/2020.

Hence it makes perfect sense for him to deny any linkage between Fed policy and market direction & shake it off to "confidence in the economy".

For such an admission would reveal the blatant conflict.
That's why in other offices people are forced to divest to avoid the conflict.

Am I the only one baffled by the blatant conflict of interest?
Powell is all long ETFs in his personal holdings which are vast.
If the right economic policy is to taper as some have called for he would hurt his personal financial interest.

Like it or not he's conflicted.
Looking forward to Jay Powell delivering new market highs again tomorrow and absolutely not contribute to inequality by doing so.

For tracking bull markets, there's an array of metrics and indicators, but a few patterns are key to watch

- HODLers distributing their wealth
- New speculators increasing their positions
- Miners reaching peak profitability

Read our full analysisüëá
https://t.co/e6FiIPN6Zv

6/7
Lastly we look at miners, who are some of the biggest #Bitcoin bulls on the network, having significant CAPEX on the line.

By observing their unspent $BTC rewards, we can observe when miners are distributing or accumulating coins.

Live Chart: https://t.co/P2Dt2eVjF6 https://t.co/Kvfdzbo4z1

5/7
A cyclical metric that captures this wealth transfer event is the R.HODL Ratio by @PositiveCrypto

This metric takes a ratio between 1-2yr old coins and very young 1-week old coins

This gives insight into the balance of old vs new hands.

Live Chart: https://t.co/FnwoKtE7Fa https://t.co/SZTmE19Krj

4/7
As bull markets progress, old hands distribute a portion of $BTC wealth to new speculators.

As expensive coins change hands, the Realized Cap HODL waves for coins younger than 3 months will swell, typically in three waves.

Live Chart: https://t.co/zri0gsDaSW https://t.co/WvFhhFR9Sz

3/7
When large volumes of old coins move, a proportionally large volume of coin-days are destroyed.

Coin-Days Destroyed (CDD) characterises both bull and bear cycles based on spending patterns.

We remain well below 2017 levels at present.

Live Chart: https://t.co/UZp1U76Sca https://t.co/QAgQTWWdHM

2/7
Spent Output Age Bands provide insight into when old coins are on the move.

Historically, old coins are spent to realise gains in bull markets, or in periods of high bearish volatility.

Lately, older coins have slowed their spending.

Live Chart: https://t.co/LWfhtGOZk5 https://t.co/i3Z9jGzBzq

1/7
Long term HODLers are the buyers of last resort

Their typical spending pattern is accumulation in the bear and distribution in the bull.

Realized Cap HODL waves show both swelling of HODLer supply, coin maturation and spending of profits

Live Chart: https://t.co/zri0gsDaSW https://t.co/bIa6IKVaii
